During the past decade, Syria’s displacement crisis has made the Middle East one of the world’s premier refugee-hosting regions. The measures to prevent refugees and migrants from leaving the region, and returning those who do, has made the region a zone of containment where millions remain displaced. The volume explores responses to mass migration and traces the genealogy of humanitarian containment from the Ottoman Empire and the emergence of the first refugee camps to the present-day displacement ‘crises’ and the re-bordering of Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aHumanitarianismzMiddle EastxHistory. 0aRefugee campszMiddle East. 0aRefugeeszEuropexHistory. 0aRefugeeszMiddle EastxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAnthropology (General), Refugee and Migration Studies, Development Studies.1 aAgier, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBendixsen, Synnøve Kristine Nepstad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerg, Kjersti G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerg, Kjersti G., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBryant, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChatty, Dawn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Lauri, Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoraï, Kamel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEriksen, Thomas Hylland, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoffmann, Sophia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnudsen, Are John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnudsen, Are John, eeditor.4e